# 6. 音楽はいつか

An: What do we do? The convention's gonna end soon!
Boy: ...
Boy: What am I doing wrong?
Toya: I can't say for certain, since I've only been practicing for a little while...
Toya: But as far as I can tell, you don't appear to be blowing too hard or holding your lips incorrectly.
Toya: Which means there must be another reason. All we have to do is figure out what that is...
Mafuyu: All we can do is keep trying as many different things as we can...
An: Then, let's make good use of every second that we have left! I'll do my best to help, too!
Boy: No...
Boy: I doubt there's any point.
An: What?
Boy: I still can't play, despite all the help you guys are giving me...
Boy: I don't think I'm cut out for this, after all.
Toya: ...!
Boy: But I'm glad I tried. Thank you all...
An: B-But...!
Toya: Please wait.
Boy: Huh...?
Toya: I understand why you feel like giving up.
Toya: But... That's exactly why I don't want you to. I know this is very selfish of me...
An: Toya...
Boy: ...
Toya: You mentioned how you struggle to produce a good sound, despite your best efforts.
Toya: The truth is, I've experienced something very similar.
Boy: Huh...? You have?
Toya: Yes. But it wasn't the trumpet in my case. It was the piano and the violin...
Toya: Just as you're struggling now, I had a lot of trouble producing the sound I wanted.
Toya: That ideal sound... No matter how hard I tried, I couldn't reach it.
Toya: I felt just as frustrated as you are at the moment. Every time I failed, I felt like crying, because it was a reminder of my lack of skill and talent.
Toya: I don't remember how many times I wanted to give up.
Boy: ...
Toya: However, after a year or two of practicing, my sound began improving.
Toya: It was subtle, but I started getting closer to that ideal sound I had in my head.
Boy: Really?
Toya: Yes. Again, it was very subtle.
Toya: But that made me so happy... Even though I still had to endure some very hard practices, I couldn't stop playing.
Toya: And each time I put in an honest effort, my music changed for the better.
Toya: Before I knew it, I could play even more beautifully than I had imagined.
Toya: So...
Toya: If any part of you still wishes to produce beautiful music, then I implore you to not give up here.
Toya: Because you will be able to... Someday.
Toya: At least, that's what I believe.
Boy: ...
Boy: Okay...
Boy: Then, I'll keep trying for a bit longer...!
Toya: ...! Yes, let's keep trying together.
Kanade: (That desire to play beautiful music...)
Kanade: (Oh, come to think of it...)
Toya: So, let's give it another try. Would you mind showing me again how you're buzzing your lips?
Boy: Okay!
An: Huh?
Mafuyu: That sound you just made...
Kanade: I-I did it...!!
An: Yoisaki?!
Kanade: Thank goodness...!
Kanade: That discussion you just had about wanting to play beautiful music reminded me of something I learned when I was little.
Kanade: About how important it is to have a clear mental image.
Mafuyu: A clear mental image?
Kanade: Yes. Even with good technique, it's possible to become so overly conscious of your playing that things stop working.
Kanade: Which is why it can be helpful to take a step back, clear your mind and focus only on the sound you wish to produce.
Toya: The sound you wish to produce...
Toya: Yes, you're right... I fell into the very same trap.
Toya: (Compared to when I was just practicing to get better, I always seemed to produce a much better sound when I focused on playing like Dad...)
An: So, if he does what Yoisaki says and really focuses on what he wants, then he'll be able to play properly?
Toya: Yes! Let's give it a try!
Boy: Okay!
